HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has announced an increase of 14°% in the number of citizens living with HIV or AIDS.
According to health officials, more than 820,000 people are affected in the country.
About 40,000 new cases were reported alone in the second quarter of 2018.
In contrast to the past, the transmission took place in the vast majority of new cases through sexual intercourse.
So far, HIV has spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
However, the number of people infected with HIV in this way has been reduced to almost zero, said Chinese health officials at a conference in Yunnan Province.
In comparison, however, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS has increased by 100,000 in China.
The transmission of HIV by sex is an acute problem in China's LGBT community.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against members of the LGBT community should be widespread.
On the basis of the country's conservative values, studies have estimated that 70-90% of men who have sex relations with men eventually marry women.
Many of the disease transfers are due to insufficient protection in these relationships in the field of sex.
Since 2003, the Chinese Government has, among other things, promised general access to HIV drugs to address the problem.
