With Solid, users can choose where their data is stored and who accesss which information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee gave the best chance that the intention behind Inrupt was the “world domination”.
"We need to become active now," he said on startup.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid's technology so that users can create their own personal online data storage or POD.
It can contain contact lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library and other tools for the private and corporate areas.
Similar to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, all content are available in one browser and at the same time.
The special thing about the personal online data storage is that the user can decide on his own who can access which data.
The company describes this concept as personal strengthening and development of data.
According to CEO John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company uses resources, processes and corresponding capabilities to make Solid available to everyone.
The company currently includes Berners-Lee, Bruce, some developers who have been hired to work on this project, as well as a community of voluntary programmers. Furthermore, a IBM-acquired security platform is used.
At the beginning of this week, technology developers worldwide can create their own decentralized apps with tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee announced that he and his team will not exchange with Facebook and Google about whether a comprehensive change is to be made, in which their entire business models will be completely remodelled overnight.
"We do not ask for their permission."
In a post published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt has the task of providing commercial energy generation and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new solid-based webs.
In 1994, Berners-Lee created the Internet when he founded the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been significantly involved in the debate on network neutrality.
Even with the launch of Inrupt, Berners-Lee remains the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I am extremely confident about this new era of the web," he added.
