According to The London Gazette, Colonel Vann led his battalion over the Canal de Saint-Quentin on September 29, 1918; through dense fog and under violent fire of field cannons and machine guns.
Later, he moved forward to the fire line and led the line forward with the "greatest taperness" before running forward with a field weapon in the single entrance and removing three of the military units.
Colonel Vann was shot by a German sniper on October 4, 1918; a little more than a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said that the deeds of his grandfather were something he could never live up to, and at the same time something that makes a humble one become.
Together with his brother Dr. James Vann, after the parade under the direction of the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band, he made a wreath.
Michael Vann said that he felt very honored to be able to participate in the parade, adding that the bravery of a real hero will be visible mainly through the support of many people.
