National Trust Listens to the Secret Life of Bats
In a estate in the Scottish Highlands, new research is being carried out to demonstrate how bats use the landscape in the search for food.
It is hoped that the results will enable further insights into the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and help to lead future nature conservation activities.
The study carried out by researchers at the National Trust for Scotland will detect dwarf and mosquito bats, as well as the brown long ear and bats in Inverewe Garden in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices are placed at key positions on the property to record the activities of bats throughout the season.
Employees of the NHS and volunteers will also carry out mobile tests with portable detectors.
In a sound analysis of all recordings by experts, the frequency of bat calls is determined and determines what species is doing.
A map and a report of the habitat will then be drawn up to create a detailed picture of their behaviour at landscape level.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes that the results will show which areas of habitat are most important for bats and how these are used by each species.
These data will help to determine the benefits of measures to manage habitat management, such as the creation of meadows, and show how to obtain forest areas for bats and other related species.
In the last century, the stocks of bats in Scotland and the whole of the United Kingdom have decreased significantly.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects sleeping places and leads to the loss of living space.
Windwheels and lighting can also present a risk, as can flycatchers and chemical treatment of building materials or attacks by domestic cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated echo to detect insects and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS responsible for the maintenance of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land throughout Scotland takes the theme of bats very seriously.
It has 10 trained experts carrying out regular investigations, inspections of sleeping places and sometimes rescue measures.
The organization has even established Scotland's first and only bat reserve in the three-way industry in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland's 10 bat species.
Gutswalter David Thompson explains that the property is the ideal habitat for them.
"Here in Threat we have a great area for bats," he explains.
“We have the old buildings, many old trees and an excellent living space.
But there is much we do not yet know about bats, so here and on other goods we carry out these works, which will help us to learn more about what bats need to feel at ease."
He stressed the importance of excluding first from the presence of bats before maintenance in the goods, as it was possible that the involuntary destruction of a single nest site could kill up to 400 females and young animals and erase the entire population on site.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them or destroy them or their nests.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish civil servant of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the population to help.
She explains: "We still have a lot to learn about bats, and with many of our species we do not know what their populations are all about."
