In Palu, over 16,000 people were evacuated after the disaster.
Here are some important facts about Palu and Donggala on Sulawesi Island:
Palu is the capital of the province of Central Sulawesi and is located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Sulawesi, with an estimated population of 379,800 in 2017.
The city had just celebrated its 40th anniversary when the earthquake and tsunami occurred.
Donggala is a government district that extends to the northwest of the island of Sulawesi over a coastal section of more than 300 km (180 miles).
In the government district, an administrative unit below the province, lived in 2017 estimated 299,200 people.
Fisheries and agriculture are the main sources of revenue from the economy of Central Sulawesis, particularly the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickelabbau is also important in the province, but it focuses mainly on Mrowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesis.
Palu and Donggala have been victims of earthquakes and tsunamis several times over the past 100 years, according to Indonesia's Civil Protection Authority.
In 1938, over 200 people were killed by a tsunami that destroyed hundreds of houses in Donggala.
West Donggala was hit in 1996 by a tsunami in which nine people died.
Indonesia lies on the seismic Pacific fire ring, and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Here are some of the largest earthquakes and tsunamis in recent years:
2004: A strong earthquake on the west coast of the Indonesian province of Aceh in the north of Sumatras triggered a tsunami on 26 December that met 14 countries and cost 226,000 people living in the coastal areas of the Indian Ocean, of which almost half was in Aceh.
2005: A number of severe earthquakes shook the west coast of Sumatras between the end of March and the beginning of April.
Hundreds of people died on the Nias Islands off the coast of Sumatras.
2006: An earthquake with a strength of 6.8 shook the south of Java, Indonesia's most populous island and triggered a tsunami that hit the south coast and claimed nearly 700 deaths.
2009: An earthquake with a strength of 7.6 met the city of Padang, the capital of the province of West Sumatra.
More than 1,100 people were killed.
2010: An earthquake with a strength of 7.5 shook one of the Mentawai Islands in front of Sumatra and triggered a tsunami of up to 10 meters high that destroyed dozen villages and demanded about 300 human lives.
2016: A slight earthquake shook the government district of Pidie Jaya in Aceh and caused destruction and panic when people were reminded of the destruction of the deadly earthquake and tsunami of 2004.
This time, no tsunami was triggered, but more than 100 people died from falling buildings.
2018: Heavy earthquakes hit the Indonesian island of Lombok popular among tourists and demanded more than 500 deaths on the north side of the island.
The earthquake destroyed thousands of buildings and thousands of tourists were temporarily stranded on the island.
