Syria is 'prepared' for the return of refugees, according to the Foreign Minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and asks for help to rebuild the land destroyed by the war that lasts for seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem stated that the situation in the country is improving.
"Today, thanks to the progress made in the fight against terrorism, the situation on the ground is more stable and secure," he said.
The government rebuilds the areas destroyed by terrorists to restore normality.
All the conditions were now in place for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures aimed at their everyday life and living conditions.
The UN estimates that over 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the beginning of the war in 2011.
A further six million people still living in the country need humanitarian aid.
Al-Moualem said that the Syrian government welcomed help in the reconstruction of the devastated country.
However, he stressed that there would be no conditions for aid from countries that had supported the uprising.
